# No Backwards Compatibility

This project does not maintain backwards compatibility. Prefer clean, breaking changes over compatibility layers.

## Default behavior

- Do not add deprecation shims, aliases, or re-exports to keep old APIs working
- Do not keep dual code paths for old and new behavior
- Do not add version checks, feature flags, or fallbacks solely to support prior behavior
- Remove dead code, legacy fields, and obsolete migrations when you touch related code
- Rename, move, or delete APIs directly instead of leaving wrappers

## When changing interfaces

- Update all call sites in the same change when practical
- Delete old types, endpoints, config keys, and CLI flags instead of marking them deprecated
- Change schemas and migrations directly; do not write multi-step compatibility migrations unless the user explicitly asks

## Exceptions

Only preserve backwards compatibility when the user explicitly requests it in the current task.

## Examples

```rust
// ❌ BAD — compatibility shim
pub use fetch_user as get_user;
pub fn fetch_user_legacy(id: &str) -> User { /* old shape */ }

// ✅ GOOD — one API, breaking change applied everywhere
pub fn fetch_user(id: &str) -> User { /* new shape */ }
```

```rust
// ❌ BAD — dual behavior
if use_legacy_parser {
    return parse_v1(data);
}
parse_v2(data)

// ✅ GOOD — remove v1 and migrate callers
parse_v2(data)
```
